the Flower Parent and Child / Haha Bangla Manus sculpture currently on display at Roppongi Hills @roppongihillsofficial in Tokyo is the larges among the sculptures I have produced so far. It will be on display until September 26, 2021. I believe more people will soon be able to visit Tokyo, and I would be very happy if you could come see this work. 

On display until September 26, 2021
Roppongi Hills, Roku-Roku Plaza

Haha Bangla Manus, 2020
Gold leaf on Bronze
10,451 x 7,300 x 10,000 mm

Haha Bangla Manus, 2020-2021
video, 1min 21sec

My friend Kashiwa Sato @kashiwasato , the designer, currently has an exhibition going on at the National Art Center, Tokyo @thenationalartcentertokyo . I have been a friendly marketing ambassador, if you will, and filmed some conversations with him. He is probably best recognized internationally for his work for UNIQLO @uniqlo . Kashiwa Sato is very popular in Japan, with a few publications on his work philosophy and principles, which have been translated into Chinese as well. In Japan, people must find it bizarre that Kashiwa-san and I are good friends. I say this because in this country, contemporary artists like myself are not at all respected; I, in particular, am notorious as a traitor who feeds a contorted version of Japanese culture to overseas audiences. In Japanese society, designers, film and animation directors, manga authors, and game designers hold high esteem. Kashiwa-san is one of the very rare, few people who have maintained friendship with me. 
I hope you’ll check out our conversations in the video.

node.text:
I listened to Bad Bunny’s @badbunnypr song “Yonaguni” on Spotify. Last year, his “DÁKITI” took the world by storm, and in the past few months I kept hearing the Japanese phrase “doko ni imasuka” on Spotify, which piqued my interest. Upon listening to the song carefully, I became aware that it was the one called “Yonaguni”.
Within Japan there are many listeners who are curious about the Japanese lyrics Bad Bunny sings. Things are heating up here, with blogs popping up exploring questions such as: “Why Japanese?” and “Why Yonaguni?” 
A singer from Puerto Rico sings about the exoticism of Yonaguni Island in faraway Japan, and I, as a Japanese, am moved by the wonder of it. It's a very uplifting, fluffy experience.
I have managed to gain fans around the world for my work that refines and sublimates Japanese manga and anime culture as art, but after the moving experience of listening to "Yonaguni", I wanted to incorporate a mysterious mood of exoticism into my work as well.
These days I am deeply involved in the world of Japanese ceramics, in which indigenous, mucky “history of Japan” seems to wriggle. There is an exoticism to it, as though I am traveling through a history unknown to the rest of the world.
I hope to post about things of that nature here from time to time.
Please also check out @tonari_no_murata and @tonari_no_totoya for ceramics projects I am involved in.

node.text:
Since the beginning of this year, I am increasingly thinking about ceramics and acting on such thoughts. In fact, thinking how fun it would be if that were my job, I have recently started creating paintings in a ceramics-like context. Of course, since painting doesn’t involve a firing process, it amounts to a pictorial reinterpretation of a ceramics worldview. 

And I am now considering placing more weight on my commitment to real, fired ceramic works. 

One day, a certain genre of art starts inundating my eyes, piquing my interest, leading me to gather what information I can on it. After a while, a reliable filter starts to form inside me, and I start to understand which work is good, and which work has no relevance to me. Until I can establish such a standard for evaluation, I indiscriminately absorb everything in sight. 
In the case of my experience with ceramics, at first I bought all sorts of ceramic works I could get my hands on. I bought and bought and bought. I have more than 10,000 works in my collection and haven’t even tried to count them (though I intend to take inventory soon). Then, this year, I started selling some ceramic works I made in collaboration with Shin Murata. That is, I am beginning to pose some questions to the world with my sense of values regarding ceramics. 
As this has been a test run, we haven’t produced or offered many for sale, but I felt a meaningful reaction, so I intend to shift gear and produce ceramic works with more frequency. Since my concept is utterly different from those of other ceramicists, people may resent my undertaking as perverse, but I want to try striking out aggressively.

僕の2000年東京から始まった、スーパーフラットシリーズ三部作、キュレーション展のタイトルです。この図柄は、そのタイトルのSuper FLAT Coloriage Little boyのスプレー文字をメインに据えた作品です。
スーパーフラット展は2000年、東京の渋谷のPARCO @parco_shibuya_official というデパートのギャラリーで始めました。その後ロサンゼルスMOCA @moca のパシフィック・デザイン・センターというところで2001年にやり、同年にミネアポリスのウォーカー・アート・センター @walkerartcenter と、シアトルのワシントン大学のミュージアムでもやりました。
その後カルティエ・ファウンデーション @fondationcartier で、2002年に「コロリアージュ」というタイトルで、そのキュレーションシリーズのPART２をやって、PART３は2005年に「リトルボーイ」と謳ってニューヨークのジャパン・ソサエティ @japansociety でやり、アメリカの批評家大賞を頂きました。
スーパーフラットとは何かというと、日本の伝統的な絵画から、現代の漫画・アニメにまで共通してみられる、画面の立体感のなさ、平面性、装飾性、遊戯性を示すものであり、また、敗戦後の日本社会の階層性のなさやフラットさをも示すものです。
コロリアージュはスーパーフラットで出した、敗戦後の日本文化におけるサブカルチャーの中に生まれた、美的センスの推移を追っかけたものです。例えば、「ポケモン」とか「A BATHING APE」とか、そういったサブカルチャーこそ、日本の美意識の王道なんじゃないかという問い掛けでした。「リトルボーイ」は、広島に落ちた原爆の愛称に由来させ、そのトラウマが造った美の系譜を読み解きました。
この３つの展覧会のキュレーションによって僕自身、アーティストとしての立ち位置を表明しましたし、僕の考え方をアート界に表明できました。それらを今一度、僕のシグナチャーとしてスプレー文字を作ったのが今回の作品です。

These are the titles of the trilogy of Superflat exhibitions I curated starting in 2000 in Tokyo.The image shows a design with the titles, Superflat, Coloriage, and Little Boy, rendered in spray-painted lettering.
 I started the Superflat exhibition in 2000 at a gallery in a department store called PARCO in Shibuya @parco_shibuya_official , Tokyo. In 2001, I brought the exhibition to the Pacific Design Center @moca at MOCA in Los Angeles, which then traveled to the Walker Art Center @walkerartcenter in Minneapolis and the Henry Art Gallery at the University of Washington in Seattle.
I subsequently organized Part 2 of the curated series, titled Coloriage, at the Cartier Foundation @fondationcartier in 2002 and Part 3, titled Little Boy, at the Japan Society in New York @japansociety in 2005.  The latter won an award from the Association of Art Critics in the US.
 The term Superflat represents the flatness, ornamentation, playfulness, and the lack of three-dimensionality of the pictorial surface commonly found in traditional Japanese paintings as well as contemporary manga and anime, while also pointing to the flatness and lack of hierarchy in post-war Japanese society.
 In Cololiage I tried to trace the transition of aesthetic senses that emerged in the subcultures of post-war Japanese culture that I had presented in Superflat. For example, I proposed that subcultures like Pokémon and A Bathing Ape may represent the mainstream Japanese aesthetics. The title Little Boy was derived from the nickname of the atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima, and I tried to decipher the genealogy of beauty created by this trauma.
 By curating these three exhibitions, I have expressed my position as an artist and presented my way of thinking to the art world. This time, I created these spray-painted letterings as my signature to revisit them.
